# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rigid-body-dynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The direction ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}/\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ is normal to the instantaneous plane of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The sense of angular velocity is conventionally specified by the right-hand rule, implying clockwise rotations (as viewed on the plane of rotation); negation (multiplication by −1) leaves the magnitude unchanged but flips the axis in the opposite direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The magnitude of this vector, $\omega =\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ , represents the *angular speed*, the angular rate at which the object rotates (spins or revolves).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The angular velocity as given above for point particles, is called orbital angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] A rigid body rotating about a fixed axis has each point of the body having the same orbital angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Hence such a rigid body can be given an angular velocity (called spin angular velocity) equal to the orbital angular velocity of each point in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The angular velocity, as given above for rotation in a fixed circle at constant speed, can be generalized to more general motion in three dimensions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Angular velocity has dimension of per unit time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The SI unit of angular velocity is radians per second,.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The radian is a dimensionless quantity, thus the SI units of angular velocity are dimensionally equivalent to reciprocal seconds, s−1, although rad/s is preferable to avoid confusion with **rotational velocity** in units of hertz (also equivalent to s−1).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] If angle is measured in radians, the linear velocity is the radius times the angular velocity, ⁠ $v=r\omega$ ⁠.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] With orbital radius 42000 km from the Earth's center, the satellite's tangential speed through space is thus *v* = 42000 km × 0.26/h ≈ 11000 km/h.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The angular velocity is positive since the satellite travels prograde with the Earth's rotation (the same direction as the rotation of Earth).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In the simplest case of circular motion at radius ⁠ r ⁠, with position given by the angular displacement $\phi (t)$ from the x-axis, the orbital angular velocity is the rate of change of angle with respect to time: ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {d\phi }{dt}}$ ⁠.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] If $\phi$ is measured in radians, the arc-length from the positive x-axis around the circle to the particle is ⁠ $\ell =r\phi$ ⁠, and the linear velocity is ⁠ $\textstyle v(t)={\frac {d\ell }{dt}}=r\omega (t)$ ⁠, so that ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {v}{r}}$ ⁠.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In the general case of a particle moving in the plane, the orbital angular velocity is the rate at which the position vector relative to a chosen origin "sweeps out" angle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The diagram shows the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ from the origin O to a particle ⁠ P ⁠, with its polar coordinates ⁠ $(r,\phi )$ ⁠.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] When there is no radial component, the particle moves around the origin in a circle; but when there is no cross-radial component, it moves in a straight line from the origin.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Since radial motion leaves the angle unchanged, only the cross-radial component of linear velocity contributes to angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Here the cross-radial speed $v_{\perp }$ is the signed magnitude of ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{\perp }$ ⁠, positive for counter-clockwise motion, negative for clockwise.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] These formulas may be derived doing ⁠ $\mathbf {r} =(r\cos(\varphi ),r\sin(\varphi ))$ ⁠, being r a function of the distance to the origin with respect to time, and $\varphi$ a function of the angle between the vector and the x-axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In two dimensions, angular velocity is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the radius vector turns counter-clockwise, and negative if clockwise.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Angular velocity then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In three-dimensional space, we again have the position vector **r** of a moving particle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Here, orbital angular velocity is a pseudovector whose magnitude is the rate at which **r** sweeps out angle (in radians per unit of time), and whose direction is perpendicular to the instantaneous plane in which **r** sweeps out angle (i.e. the plane spanned by **r** and **v**).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] However, as there are *two* directions perpendicular to any plane, an additional condition is necessary to uniquely specify the direction of the angular velocity; conventionally, the right-hand rule is used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Let the pseudovector $\mathbf {u}$ be the unit vector perpendicular to the plane spanned by **r** and **v**, so that the right-hand rule is satisfied (i.e. the instantaneous direction of angular displacement is counter-clockwise looking from the top of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] where ⁠ $\theta$ ⁠ is the angle between ⁠ $\mathbf {r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Given a rotating frame of three linearly independent unit coordinate vectors, at each instant in time, there always exists a common axis (called the axis of rotation) around which all three vectors rotate with the same angular speed and in the same angular direction (clockwise or counterclockwise).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In such a frame, each vector may be considered as a moving particle with constant scalar radius.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] A collection of such particles is called a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In larger than 3 spatial dimensions, the interpretation of spin angular velocity as a pseudovector is not valid; however, it may be characterized by a more general type of object known as an antisymmetric rank-2 tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The addition of angular velocity vectors for frames is also defined by the usual vector addition (composition of linear movements), and can be useful to decompose the rotation as in a gimbal.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] All components of the vector can be calculated as derivatives of the parameters defining the moving frames (Euler angles or rotation matrices).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Consider a rigid body rotating about a fixed point O.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Construct a reference frame in the body consisting of an orthonormal set of vectors $\mathbf {e} _{1},\mathbf {e} _{2},\mathbf {e} _{3}$ fixed to the body and with their common origin at O.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] where ${\dot {\mathbf {e} }}_{i}={\frac {d\mathbf {e} _{i}}{dt}}$ is the time rate of change of the frame vector ⁠ $\mathbf {e} _{i},i=1,2,3$ ⁠, due to the rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] as that formula defines angular velocity for a *single point* about O, while the formula in this section applies to a frame or rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] In the case of a rigid body a *single* ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has to account for the motion of *all* particles in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] Euler proved that the projections of the angular velocity pseudovector on each of these three axes is the derivative of its associated angle (which is equivalent to decomposing the instantaneous rotation into three instantaneous Euler rotations).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] This basis is not orthonormal and it is difficult to use, but now the velocity vector can be changed to the fixed frame or to the moving frame with just a change of bases.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] where ${\hat {\mathbf {i} }},{\hat {\mathbf {j} }},{\hat {\mathbf {k} }}$ are unit vectors for the frame fixed in the moving body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] This example has been made using the Z-X-Z convention for Euler angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] The scalar elements above correspond to the angular velocity vector components ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}=(\omega _{x},\omega _{y},\omega _{z})$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] This is an *infinitesimal rotation matrix*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] where ${\boldsymbol {r}}$ is a position vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/angular-velocity] When multiplied by a time difference, it results in the *angular displacement tensor*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] In classical mechanics, the **coefficient of restitution** (**COR**, also denoted by ***e***), is a measure of the springiness of collisions between two surfaces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The COR is a property of a *pair* of objects in a collision, not a single object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] If a given object collides with two different objects, each collision has its own COR.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] When a single object is described as having a given coefficient of restitution, as if it were an intrinsic property without reference to a second object, some assumptions have been made – for example that the collision is with another identical object, or with a perfectly rigid wall.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] In a basic analysis of collisions, *e* is generally treated as a dimensionless constant, independent of the mass and relative velocities of the two objects, with the collision being treated as effectively instantaneous.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] An example often used for teaching is the collision of two idealised billiard balls.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] Real world interactions may be more complicated, for example where the internal structure of the objects needs to be taken into account, or where there are more complex effects happening during the time between initial contact and final separation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] This is sometimes known as the **restitution equation**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] For a perfectly elastic collision, *e = 1* and the objects rebound with the same relative speed with which they approached.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] For a perfectly inelastic collision *e = 0* and the objects do not rebound at all.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The coefficient of restitution can be thought of as a measure of the extent to which energy is conserved when an object bounces off a surface.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] In practical situations, the coefficient of restitution between two bodies may have to be determined experimentally, for example using the Leeb rebound hardness test.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] This uses a tip of tungsten carbide, one of the hardest substances available, dropped onto test samples from a specific height.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] A comprehensive study of coefficients of restitution in dependence on material properties (elastic moduli, rheology), direction of impact, coefficient of friction and adhesive properties of impacting bodies can be found in Willert (2020).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] Thin-faced golf club drivers utilize a "trampoline effect" that creates drives of a greater distance as a result of the flexing and subsequent release of stored energy which imparts greater impulse to the ball.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The USGA (America's governing golfing body) tests drivers for COR and has placed the upper limit at 0.83.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] COR is a function of rates of clubhead speeds and diminish as clubhead speed increase.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] In the report COR ranges from 0.845 for 90 mph to as low as 0.797 at 130 mph.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The above-mentioned "trampoline effect" shows this since it reduces the rate of stress of the collision by increasing the time of the collision.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The International Table Tennis Federation specifies that the ball shall bounce up 24–26 cm when dropped from a height of 30.5 cm on to a standard steel block, implying a COR of 0.887 to 0.923.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/coefficient-of-restitution] The International Basketball Federation (FIBA) rules require that the ball rebound to a height of between 1035 and 1085 mm when dropped from a height of 1800 mm, implying a COR between 0.758 and 0.776.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] In classical mechanics, **impulse** (symbolized by **J** or **Imp**) is the change in momentum of an object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] It is most often used to describe forces which act over short time periods, specifically in the case of impacts and collisions, for which it gets its namesake.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Impulse is a vector quantity, meaning it has both a magnitude, which describes the amount by which the momentum changed, and a direction, which describes the direction in which the momentum changed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] For a force acting over a short time, the impulse is often *idealized* so that the change in momentum produced by the force is modelled as happening instantaneously.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] This sort of change is a step change, and is not physically possible.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] However, this is a useful model for computing the effects of ideal collisions (such as in videogame physics engines).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Additionally, in rocketry, the term "total impulse" is commonly used and is considered synonymous with the term "impulse".
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Impulse has the same units and dimensions (LMT−1) as momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] The SI unit of impulse is the newton-second (N⋅s), and the dimensionally equivalent unit of momentum is the kilogram-metre per second (kg⋅m/s).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] The corresponding English engineering unit is the pound-second (lbf⋅s), and in the British Gravitational System, the unit is the slug-foot per second (slug⋅ft/s).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] This is often called the impulse–momentum theorem (analogous to the work–energy theorem).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] As a result of the previous result, an impulse may also be regarded as the change in momentum of an object to which a resultant force is applied.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] The application of Newton's second law for variable mass allows impulse and momentum to be used as analysis tools for jet- or rocket-propelled vehicles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] In the case of rockets, the impulse imparted can be normalized by unit of propellant expended, to create a performance parameter, specific impulse, the impulse per unit mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] This fact can be used to derive the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, which relates the vehicle's propulsive change in velocity to the engine's specific impulse (or nozzle exhaust velocity) and the vehicle's propellant-mass ratio.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Newton's second law is often written as $\mathbf {F} ={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} }{\mathrm {d} t}}.$ But this is the case only when there is no mass *transfer* into or out of **p**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] When the mass of an object changes by exuding or accumulating mass, the momentum has a time dependence in its mass aspect as well as in its velocity aspect.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Thus, using either the step-wise impulse method or the infinitesimal Newtonian force method work in this case.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Suppose our previous example was for a rocket.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/impulse-physics] Then, using the equation for **J**, we have that the specific impulse *I*sp is $I_{\mathrm {sp} }=\mathbf {v} -\mathbf {u} .$ In this case, we call this quantity the exhaust velocity since it is equal to the velocity at which the material is leaving the rocket relative to the frame of the rocket.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] To improve their maneuverability, combat aircraft are designed to minimize moments of inertia, while civil aircraft often are not.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The **moment of inertia** (also known as **mass moment of inertia**, **angular/rotational mass**, **second moment of mass**, or **rotational inertia**) is a measure of how difficult it is to change the rotation rate of a rigid body about a given axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It is the ratio between the torque applied and the resulting angular acceleration about that axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It plays the same role in rotational motion as mass does in linear motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A body's moment of inertia about a particular axis depends on both the mass and its distribution relative to the axis, increasing with mass and distance from the axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a point mass, the moment of inertia is simply the mass times the square of the perpendicular distance to the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a rigid composite system is the sum of the moments of inertia of its component subsystems (all taken about the same axis).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Its simplest definition is the second moment of mass with respect to distance from an axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a body is forced to rotate in a plane, then only the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the plane, a scalar value, matters.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a body is allowed to rotate in all three dimensions, then its moment is described by a symmetric 3-by-3 matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This symmetric matrix can be orthogonally diagonalized by a set of mutually perpendicular principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Torques around these principal axes act independently of each other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] When a body is free to rotate around an axis, torque must be applied to change its angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The amount of torque needed to cause any given angular acceleration (the rate of change in angular velocity) is proportional to the moment of inertia of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Moments of inertia may be expressed in units of kilogram metre squared (kg·m2) in SI units and pound-foot-squared (lb·ft2) in imperial or US units.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia plays the role in rotational kinetics that mass (inertia) plays in linear kinetics—both characterize the resistance of a body to changes in its motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia depends on how mass is distributed around an axis of rotation, and will vary depending on the chosen axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a point-like mass, the moment of inertia about some axis is given by $mr^{2}$ , where r is the distance of the point from the axis, and m is the mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For an extended rigid body, the moment of inertia is just the sum of all the small pieces of mass multiplied by the square of their distances from the axis in rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For an extended body of a regular shape and uniform density, this summation sometimes produces a simple expression that depends on the dimensions, shape and total mass of the object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In 1673, Christiaan Huygens introduced this parameter in his study of the oscillation of a body hanging from a pivot, known as a compound pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The term *moment of inertia* ("momentum inertiae" in Latin) was introduced by Leonhard Euler in his book *Theoria motus corporum solidorum seu rigidorum* in 1765, and it is incorporated into Euler's second law.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The natural frequency of oscillation of a compound pendulum is obtained from the ratio of the torque imposed by gravity on the mass of the pendulum to the resistance to acceleration defined by the moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Comparison of this natural frequency to that of a simple pendulum consisting of a single point of mass provides a mathematical formulation for moment of inertia of an extended body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia also appears in momentum, kinetic energy, and in Newton's laws of motion for a rigid body as a physical parameter that combines its shape and mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] There is an interesting difference in the way moment of inertia appears in planar and spatial movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Planar movement has a single scalar that defines the moment of inertia, while for spatial movement the same calculations yield a 3 × 3 matrix of moments of inertia, called the inertia matrix or inertia tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a rotating flywheel is used in a machine to resist variations in applied torque to smooth its rotational output.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of an airplane about its longitudinal, horizontal and vertical axes determine how steering forces on the control surfaces of its wings, elevators and rudder(s) affect the plane's motions in roll, pitch and yaw.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The **moment of inertia** is defined as the product of mass of section and the square of the distance between the reference axis and the centroid of the section.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It is denoted with the symbol *I* or *J*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If the angular momentum of a system is constant, then as the moment of inertia gets smaller, the angular velocity must increase.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This occurs when spinning figure skaters pull in their outstretched arms or divers curl their bodies into a tuck position during a dive, to spin faster.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, the moment of inertia of the pendulum depends on both the mass m of a body and its geometry, or shape, as defined by the distance r to the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This simple formula generalizes to define moment of inertia for an arbitrarily shaped body as the sum of all the elemental point masses *dm* each multiplied by the square of its perpendicular distance r to an axis k.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] An arbitrary object's moment of inertia thus depends on the spatial distribution of its mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In general, given an object of mass m, an effective radius k can be defined, dependent on a particular axis of rotation, with such a value that its moment of inertia around the axis is $I=mk^{2},$ where k is known as the radius of gyration around the axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Mathematically, the moment of inertia of a simple pendulum is the ratio of the torque due to gravity about the pivot of a pendulum to its angular acceleration about that pivot point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The force of gravity on the mass of a simple pendulum generates a torque ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F}$ around the axis perpendicular to the plane of the pendulum movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Here $\mathbf {r}$ is the distance vector from the torque axis to the pendulum center of mass, and $\mathbf {F}$ is the net force on the mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Associated with this torque is an angular acceleration, ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ , of the string and mass around this axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Since the mass is constrained to a circle the tangential acceleration of the mass is $\mathbf {a} ={\boldsymbol {\alpha }}\times \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] (The second to last step uses the vector triple product expansion with the perpendicularity of ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ and $\mathbf {r}$ .) The quantity $I=mr^{2}$ is the *moment of inertia* of this single mass around the pivot point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This shows that the quantity $I=mr^{2}$ is how mass combines with the shape of a body to define rotational inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of an arbitrarily shaped body is the sum of the values $mr^{2}$ for all of the elements of mass in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A compound pendulum is a body formed from an assembly of particles of continuous shape that rotates rigidly around a pivot.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Its moment of inertia is the sum of the moments of inertia of each of the particles that it is composed of.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Measuring this frequency of oscillation over small angular displacements provides an effective way of measuring moment of inertia of a body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A simple pendulum that has the same natural frequency as a compound pendulum defines the length L from the pivot to a point called the center of oscillation of the compound pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This point also corresponds to the center of percussion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The seconds pendulum, which provides the "tick" and "tock" of a grandfather clock, takes one second to swing from side-to-side.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This is a period of two seconds, or a natural frequency of $\pi \ \mathrm {rad/s}$ for the pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Notice that the distance to the center of oscillation of the seconds pendulum must be adjusted to accommodate different values for the local acceleration of gravity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Kater's pendulum is a compound pendulum that uses this property to measure the local acceleration of gravity, and is called a gravimeter.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a complex system such as a vehicle or airplane around its vertical axis can be measured by suspending the system from three points to form a trifilar pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A trifilar pendulum is a platform supported by three wires designed to oscillate in torsion around its vertical centroidal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The period of oscillation of the trifilar pendulum yields the moment of inertia of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Moment of inertia of area is also known as the second moment of area and its physical meaning is completely different from the mass moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] These calculations are commonly used in civil engineering for structural design of beams and columns.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Cross-sectional areas calculated for vertical moment of the x-axis $I_{xx}$ and horizontal moment of the y-axis $I_{yy}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia about an axis of a body is calculated by summing $mr^{2}$ for every particle in the body, where r is the perpendicular distance to the specified axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] To see how moment of inertia arises in the study of the movement of an extended body, it is convenient to consider a rigid assembly of point masses.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Consider the kinetic energy of an assembly of N masses $m_{i}$ that lie at the distances $r_{i}$ from the pivot point P , which is the nearest point on the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, moment of inertia is a physical property that combines the mass and distribution of the particles around the rotation axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Notice that rotation about different axes of the same body yield different moments of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a continuous body rotating about a specified axis is calculated in the same way, except with infinitely many point particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Here, the function $\rho$ gives the mass density at each point $(x,y,z)$ , $\mathbf {r}$ is a vector perpendicular to the axis of rotation and extending from a point on the rotation axis to a point $(x,y,z)$ in the solid, and the integration is evaluated over the volume V of the body Q .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a flat surface is similar with the mass density being replaced by its areal mass density with the integral evaluated over its area.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a **compound pendulum** constructed from a thin disc mounted at the end of a thin rod that oscillates around a pivot at the other end of the rod, begins with the calculation of the moment of inertia of the thin rod and thin disc about their respective centers of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A list of moments of inertia formulas for standard body shapes provides a way to obtain the moment of inertia of a complex body as an assembly of simpler shaped bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The parallel axis theorem is used to shift the reference point of the individual bodies to the reference point of the assembly.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] As one more example, consider the moment of inertia of a solid sphere of constant density about an axis through its center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This is determined by summing the moments of inertia of the thin discs that can form the sphere whose centers are along the axis chosen for consideration.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a mechanical system is constrained to move parallel to a fixed plane, then the rotation of a body in the system occurs around an axis $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ perpendicular to this plane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In this case, the moment of inertia of the mass in this system is a scalar known as the *polar moment of inertia*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The definition of the polar moment of inertia can be obtained by considering momentum, kinetic energy and Newton's laws for the planar movement of a rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For planar movement the angular velocity vector is directed along the unit vector $\mathbf {k}$ which is perpendicular to the plane of movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This defines the relative position vector and the velocity vector for the rigid system of the particles moving in a plane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia $I_{\mathbf {C} }$ about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass is known as the *polar moment of inertia*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Specifically, it is the second moment of mass with respect to the orthogonal distance from an axis (or pole).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a given amount of angular momentum, a decrease in the moment of inertia results in an increase in the angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Figure skaters can change their moment of inertia by pulling in their arms.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, the angular velocity achieved by a skater with outstretched arms results in a greater angular velocity when the arms are pulled in, because of the reduced moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A figure skater is not, however, a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia $I_{\mathbf {C} }$ is the *polar moment of inertia* of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p01] where $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}\times \mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}=\mathbf {0}$ , and $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}\times \mathbf {\hat {t}} _{i}=\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles $P_{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The scalar moments of inertia appear as elements in a matrix when a system of particles is assembled into a rigid body that moves in three-dimensional space.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This inertia matrix appears in the calculation of the angular momentum, kinetic energy and resultant torque of the rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let the system of n particles, $P_{i},i=1,\dots ,n$ be located at the coordinates $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ with velocities $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ relative to a fixed reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The kinetic energy of a rigid system of particles can be formulated in terms of the center of mass and a matrix of mass moments of inertia of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Since the center of mass is defined by $\sum _{i=1}^{n}m_{i}\Delta \mathbf {r} _{i}=0$ , the second term in this equation is zero.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The inertia matrix appears in the application of Newton's second law to a rigid assembly of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The resultant torque on this system is, ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\sum _{i=1}^{n}\left(\mathbf {r_{i}} -\mathbf {R} \right)\times m_{i}\mathbf {a} _{i},$ where $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ is the acceleration of the particle $P_{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The inertia matrix of a body depends on the choice of the reference point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] There is a useful relationship between the inertia matrix relative to the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ and the inertia matrix relative to another point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This relationship is called the parallel axis theorem.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {C}$ be the center of mass of the rigid system, then $\mathbf {R} =(\mathbf {R} -\mathbf {C} )+\mathbf {C} =\mathbf {d} +\mathbf {C} ,$ where $\mathbf {d}$ is the vector from the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ to the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The first term is the inertia matrix $\mathbf {I_{C}}$ relative to the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The second and third terms are zero by definition of the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] And the last term is the total mass of the system multiplied by the square of the skew-symmetric matrix $[\mathbf {d} ]$ constructed from $\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The result is the parallel axis theorem, $\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {R} }=\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {C} }-M[\mathbf {d} ]^{2},$ where $\mathbf {d}$ is the vector from the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ to the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let a rigid assembly of n particles, $P_{i},i=1,\dots ,n$ , have coordinates $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Choose $\mathbf {R}$ as a reference point and compute the moment of inertia around a line L defined by the unit vector $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ through the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ , $\mathbf {L} (t)=\mathbf {R} +t\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This shows that the inertia matrix can be used to calculate the moment of inertia of a body around any specified rotation axis in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] For the same object, different axes of rotation will have different moments of inertia about those axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] In general, the moments of inertia are not equal unless the object is symmetric about all axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The **moment of inertia tensor** is a convenient way to summarize all moments of inertia of an object with one quantity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] It may be calculated with respect to any point in space, although for practical purposes the center of mass is most commonly used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Note that, by the definition, $\mathbf {I}$ is a symmetric tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Here $I_{xx}$ denotes the moment of inertia around the x -axis when the objects are rotated around the x-axis, $I_{xy}$ denotes the moment of inertia around the y -axis when the objects are rotated around the x -axis, and so on.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] These quantities can be generalized to an object with distributed mass, described by a mass density function, in a similar fashion to the scalar moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A product of inertia term such as $I_{12}$ is obtained by the computation $I_{12}=\mathbf {e} _{1}\cdot \mathbf {I} \cdot \mathbf {e} _{2},$ and can be interpreted as the moment of inertia around the x -axis when the object rotates around the y -axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The components of tensors of degree two can be assembled into a matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] It is common in rigid body mechanics to use notation that explicitly identifies the x , y , and z -axes, such as $I_{xx}$ and $I_{xy}$ , for the components of the inertia tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] There are some CAD and CAE applications such as SolidWorks, Unigraphics NX/Siemens NX and MSC Adams that use an alternate convention for the products of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If one has the inertia data $(I_{xx},I_{yy},I_{zz},I_{xy},I_{xz},I_{yz})$ without knowing which inertia convention that has been used, it can be determined if one also has the principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Next, one calculates the eigenvectors for the two matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The matrix whose eigenvectors are parallel to the principal axes corresponds to the inertia convention that has been used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The distance r of a particle at $\mathbf {x}$ from the axis of rotation passing through the origin in the $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ direction is $\left|\mathbf {x} -\left(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {\hat {n}} \right)\mathbf {\hat {n}} \right|$ , where $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is a unit vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] For multiple particles, we need only recall that the moment of inertia is additive in order to see that this formula is correct.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {I} _{0}$ be the inertia tensor of a body calculated at its center of mass, and $\mathbf {R}$ be the displacement vector of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {R}$ be the matrix that represents a body's rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The use of the inertia matrix in Newton's second law assumes its components are computed relative to axes parallel to the inertial frame and not relative to a body-fixed reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This means that as the body moves the components of the inertia matrix change with time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] In contrast, the components of the inertia matrix measured in a body-fixed frame are constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Notice that $\mathbf {A}$ changes as the body moves, while $\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {C} }^{B}$ remains constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Measured in the body frame, the inertia matrix is a constant real symmetric matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The columns of the rotation matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ define the directions of the principal axes of the body, and the constants $I_{1}$ , $I_{2}$ , and $I_{3}$ are called the **principal moments of inertia**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Sylvester (1852), and is a form of Sylvester's law of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When the body has an axis of symmetry (sometimes called the **figure axis** or **axis of figure**) then the other two moments of inertia will be identical and any axis perpendicular to the axis of symmetry will be a principal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A toy top is an example of a rotating rigid body, and the word *top* is used in the names of types of rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When all principal moments of inertia are distinct, the principal axes through center of mass are uniquely specified and the rigid body is called an **asymmetric top**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If two principal moments are the same, the rigid body is called a **symmetric top** and there is no unique choice for the two corresponding principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If all three principal moments are the same, the rigid body is called a **spherical top** (although it need not be spherical) and any axis can be considered a principal axis, meaning that the moment of inertia is the same about any axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The principal axes are often aligned with the object's symmetry axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If a rigid body has an axis of symmetry of order m , meaning it is symmetrical under rotations of 360°/*m* about the given axis, that axis is a principal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When $m>2$ , the rigid body is a symmetric top.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If a rigid body has at least two symmetry axes that are not parallel or perpendicular to each other, it is a spherical top, for example, a cube or any other Platonic solid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The motion of vehicles is often described in terms of yaw, pitch, and roll which usually correspond approximately to rotations about the three principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If the vehicle has bilateral symmetry then one of the principal axes will correspond exactly to the transverse (pitch) axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A practical example of this mathematical phenomenon is the routine automotive task of balancing a tire, which basically means adjusting the distribution of mass of a car wheel such that its principal axis of inertia is aligned with the axle so the wheel does not wobble.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Rotating molecules are also classified as asymmetric, symmetric, or spherical tops, and the structure of their rotational spectra is different for each type.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The moment of inertia matrix in body-frame coordinates is a quadratic form that defines a surface in the body called Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let ${\boldsymbol {\Lambda }}$ be the inertia matrix relative to the center of mass aligned with the principal axes, then the surface $\mathbf {x} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Lambda }}\mathbf {x} =1,$ or $I_{1}x^{2}+I_{2}y^{2}+I_{3}z^{2}=1,$ defines an ellipsoid in the body frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let a point $\mathbf {x}$ on this ellipsoid be defined in terms of its magnitude and direction, $\mathbf {x} =\|\mathbf {x} \|\mathbf {n}$ , where $\mathbf {n}$ is a unit vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In classical mechanics, a **rigid body**, also known as a **rigid object**, is a solid body in which deformation is zero or negligible, when a deforming pressure or deforming force is applied on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The distance between any two given points on a rigid body remains constant in time regardless of external forces or moments exerted on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] A rigid body is usually considered as a continuous distribution of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] *Mechanics of rigid bodies* is a field within mechanics where motions and forces of objects are studied without considering effects that can cause deformation (as opposed to mechanics of materials, where deformable objects are considered).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In the study of special relativity, a perfectly rigid body does not exist; and objects can only be assumed to be rigid if they are not moving near the speed of light, where the mass is infinitely large.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In quantum mechanics, a rigid body is usually thought of as a collection of point masses.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] For instance, molecules (consisting of the point masses: electrons and nuclei) are often seen as rigid bodies (see classification of molecules as rigid rotors).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The position of a rigid body is the position of all the particles of which it is composed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] To simplify the description of this position, we exploit the property that the body is rigid, namely that all its particles maintain the same distance relative to each other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] If the body is rigid, it is sufficient to describe the position of at least three non-collinear particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] This makes it possible to reconstruct the position of all the other particles, provided that their time-invariant position relative to the three selected particles is known.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] However, typically a different, mathematically more convenient, but equivalent approach is used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] 2. the *angular position* (also known as *orientation*, or *attitude*) of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Thus, the position of a rigid body has two components: *linear* and *angular*, respectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The same is true for other kinematic and kinetic quantities describing the motion of a rigid body, such as linear and angular velocity, acceleration, momentum, impulse, and kinetic energy.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The linear position can be represented by a vector with its tail at an arbitrary reference point in space (the origin of a chosen coordinate system) and its tip at an arbitrary point of interest on the rigid body, typically coinciding with its center of mass or centroid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] This reference point may define the origin of a coordinate system fixed to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] There are several ways to numerically describe the orientation of a rigid body, including a set of three Euler angles, a quaternion, or a direction cosine matrix (also referred to as a rotation matrix).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] All these methods actually define the orientation of a basis set (or coordinate system) which has a fixed orientation relative to the body (i.e. rotates together with the body), relative to another basis set (or coordinate system), from which the motion of the rigid body is observed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In general, when a rigid body moves, both its position and orientation vary with time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In the kinematic sense, these changes are referred to as *translation* and *rotation*, respectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Indeed, the position of a rigid body can be viewed as a hypothetic translation and rotation (roto-translation) of the body starting from a hypothetic reference position (not necessarily coinciding with a position actually taken by the body during its motion).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The linear velocity of a rigid body is a vector quantity, equal to the time rate of change of its linear position.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Thus, it is the velocity of a reference point fixed to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] During purely translational motion (motion with no rotation), all points on a rigid body move with the same velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] However, when motion involves rotation, the instantaneous velocity of any two points on the body will generally not be the same.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Two points of a rotating body will have the same instantaneous velocity only if they happen to lie on an axis parallel to the instantaneous axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In this case, rigid bodies and reference frames are indistinguishable and completely interchangeable.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The norm of a position vector is the spatial distance.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Here the coordinates of all three vectors must be expressed in coordinate frames with the same orientation.
