[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In 2D, the angular velocity is a scalar, and matrix A(t) simply represents a rotation in the *xy*-plane by an angle which is the integral of the angular velocity over time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Vehicles, walking people, etc., usually rotate according to changes in the direction of the velocity: they move forward with respect to their own orientation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Then, if the body follows a closed orbit in a plane, the angular velocity integrated over a time interval in which the orbit is completed once, is an integer times 360°.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] This integer is the winding number with respect to the origin of the velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Compare the amount of rotation associated with the vertices of a polygon.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Assume that $\mathbf {v} (\mathbf {P} )$ is a smooth 3-d vector field and O is a point in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , with $\mathbf {v} _{O}=\mathbf {v} (O)$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Denote $B_{\varepsilon }$ the ball of radius $\varepsilon$ centered at O , and $\mathbf {r} =\mathbf {P} -O$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Linearizing the velocity field at O gives $\mathbf {v} (\mathbf {P} )-\mathbf {v} _{O}=(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}\,\mathbf {r} +o(r),$ where $(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}$ is the Jacobian matrix at O .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Decompose it into symmetric and antisymmetric parts: $(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}=J_{s}+J_{a}$ , with $J_{a}$ antisymmetric.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] By linear algebra, there exists a vector ${\boldsymbol {w}}$ such that $J_{a}\mathbf {r} ={\boldsymbol {w}}\times \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In fact, direct computation shows that ${\boldsymbol {w}}={1 \over 2}\nabla \times \mathbf {v} (O)$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Now, assume a rigid body is rotating with angular velocity ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Thus ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}={\boldsymbol {w}}$ and the terms $o(r)$ and $o(\varepsilon ^{3})$ vanish identically in the above formulae.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Any point that is rigidly connected to the body can be used as reference point (origin of coordinate system *L*) to describe the linear motion of the body (the linear position, velocity and acceleration vectors depend on the choice).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Two rigid bodies are said to be different (not copies) if there is no proper rotation from one to the other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] A rigid body is called chiral if its mirror image is different in that sense, i.e., if it has either no symmetry or its symmetry group contains only proper rotations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] In the opposite case an object is called achiral: the mirror image is a copy, not a different object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] Such an object may have a symmetry plane, but not necessarily: there may also be a plane of reflection with respect to which the image of the object is a rotated version.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The latter applies for *S2n*, of which the case *n* = 1 is inversion symmetry.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] For a (rigid) rectangular transparent sheet, inversion symmetry corresponds to having on one side an image without rotational symmetry and on the other side an image such that what shines through is the image at the top side, upside down.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] A sheet with a through and through image is achiral.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The configuration space of a rigid body with one point fixed (i.e., a body with zero translational motion) is given by the underlying manifold of the rotation group SO(3).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics/rigid-body] The configuration space of a nonfixed (with non-zero translational motion) rigid body is *E*+(3), the subgroup of direct isometries of the Euclidean group in three dimensions (combinations of translations and rotations).
